  					<td align=center valign="top" width=100%><br>
  						<!--#beginContent#-->
  						<table align='center' cellpadding=5 width='85%'>  <tr><td class='spti2' width='100%'>PLAYER STRATEGY - ENCHANTER</td></tr>  <tr><td width='100%' class='db'><font class='dbti'>CAUSING MAYHEM INDIRECTLY (FIGHTING THE DEEP REDS)</font> - <small>Kibray Valsharess, Rodcet Nife</td></tr>
  <tr><td width='100%' class='db'>Finally!  At these levels you get the spells that let you contribute to a group even when they are fighting deep reds.  I use these tactics even when the range of opponents fall as low as yellow if, mixed among them, are the deep reds.  Call it indirect--and think of it as augmentation tactics.
<P>
Be sure you get a good sense of who does what in your group.  If you're fighting deep reds, you either have a full group of similar level or a smaller number of higher level comrades.  Know your healers--you will be protecting them especially.  Set the 'danger' level that a healer does not want to let any group member fall under--this will be critical for you knowing when to assist the healer in keeping the party healthy.
<P>
If you're in an open area or in a wide place in a dungeon without too much green/blue trash hanging about, summon your pet if the group is agreeable to it.  (It's an unresistable DoT if your opponent takes a swipe at you.) If in a dungeon, make sure that there are root or snare casters to keep runners from getting far (your pet chasing down a runner is the greatest danger to you).  
<P>
Load up Tashan/Tashani, a DoT that you are fond of (these often will not be resisted after Tashani and are mana-efficient), Quicken/Alacrity, Rune AND Beserker Strength if you have it (the duo allow you to cast with NO recovery time), Color Flux/Shift, Memory Blur, some version of Mesmerize (I like Mesmerization for it's ability to hold all manner of annoying lower-level trash in line).  
<P>
I usually take over the task of strength buffing.  If I am using Beserker Strength, I will usually warn the fighters and buffers that Berserker Strength will not stack with other strength buffs (hence, I use my tiny strength buff in the meantime).  
<P>
If there is a dearth of decent buffs, I will Cloud as well and I use Endure Magic if casters are among the opponents.  Shield yourself as well--you are fragile and there's no need to unnecessarily become an emergency for the healer because you weren't paying attention.  
<P>
Now--here's your trick.  Handle any buff duties you've taken over.  Rune or Beserker Strength your lure.  Quicken/Alacrity your tanks (if the battles come quickly, I typically stagger the casts since the duration will last through 2-3 fights).  If you have a pet, Quicken it (the duration seems much longer on a pet for some reason).  
<P>
Now--as the battle commences, Tashan/Tashani the opponent, try the DoT if you have plenty of mana and the opponent is not hugely more powerful than you(it will hold if you are lucky or the opponent is not actually more than 5 levels higher than you).  Watch the health bars of your comrades.  If you have a pet, you may wish to step in until the opponent takes a stray hit at you--I will often cast Color Flux to grab it's attention for a moment (your Quickened tanks will be far more annoying to it soon after).  Fall back immediately after.  Stay away from the melee!
<P>
As soon as you see your healers falling behind on keeping the tanks at 3+ bubbles of health or whatever the 'danger' level was set at, start casting Berserker Strength and/or Rune to give the healers time to catch up on the heals.  If the opponent latches onto a healer, Memory Blur it.  If any member of your party falls near that critical 2 bubbles of health, Memory Blur the opponent.  Your spells are slow!  Start early.  You do know how to use the function keys to target your group members, right?
<P>

Most of the time, you will never need to Memory Blur or DoT or Color Flux.  Your mesmerize spell should sit unused.  In fact, most fights, you'll come out of the battle with 50%+ on your mana.  Quicken/Alacrity are incredibly handy.  If your healers are on the ball, things can seem a bit boring.  But you need not worry that you will be unappreciated--even the slowest and least able of the tanks can see the difference that Quicken makes.  You can always cast an occasional gratuitous Berserker Strength, if you have it, to remind the fighters why they love you.  But when things go wrong, your Rune/Strength combo will keep people alive when a healer is simply too slow.  
<P>
Mesmerize and Color Flux is minimal crowd control for when little stuff joins in.  And that crowd control will net you plenty of admiration--just be sure your group understands how it works. 
<P>
Anyway, I hope this helps you who are considering travelling with higher-level friends or venturing deep into the dungeons.  It's proved terribly successful for me. 
		</td></tr>
  <tr><td class='db'>&nbsp;</td></tr>
